#  üç¶Vanilla (beginner):

The examples below are perfect starting points for educators new to AI-powered tool creation. Each one has a prompt, a video showing how to create it, and an example file you can download and experiment with on your own. You can use the prompts provided with any of the chatbot interfaces to generate an HTML file and experience the process.

These examples have the following in common:

* They can run from a single file located on your computer.  
* They're self-contained with no need for external data storage or complex processing.

## But wait \- I don‚Äôt know what I‚Äôm doing\!

That's ok\! Everyone starts somewhere, and we've designed multiple entry points:

* If you want to see how the process works, just choose one of the three tools below and watch the video to see how the prompt can be used with a text editor to create the app. You can then download the file and run it on your computer.  
* If you want to try prompting, choose your favorite AI model and paste the prompt in. The model will give you code that you can paste into either of the editor options under the Getting Started tab.

In either case, it might get you thinking about the tool you want to make. Remember: you don't need to be a programmer to create powerful educational tools‚Äîyou just need to clearly communicate your vision to the AI\!

## Time Management \- Pomodoro Timer

This example shows how you can build a productivity tool. It includes a prompt, a video where I talk you through the steps, and downloadable code.

| Prompt to paste into a chat: I want to make a Pomodoro style app with a big start button and big timer text in a box in the middle of the screen. ## Word Reader

## Task List Maker

This example shows how you can build a tool that will let you list all of the things you have to do, and then help you organize them into different categories of priorities.  It includes a prompt, a video where I talk you through the steps, and downloadable code.

| I want to make a tool that helps me get organized. Usually at the start of the day, I write down a list of everything I'm thinking about or need to do. Then I sort them into four categories: Now, Today, This week, and later. I want to build an app that lets me do this in a web browser. On the left side of the screen, I want a giant text box that I can type the things I need to do, separated by hitting ENTER. Then once I've written everything, I want to hit a button that floats each item into a rounded rectangular box that randomly gets placed into one of the four categories on the right side of the screen. I can then click and drag the rectangular boxes around between the categories and then decide what I want them to do. When I float my mouse over a box, I want a little trash can to show up that deletes the box. I also want to be able to type in new items as I think of them. Oh, and I want the right hand side of the screen to be saved into local storage so I don't have redo my items every time I load the page. Please make me a single HTML page with code that I can paste into an editor. I want to be able to load the page in a web browser any time I want to use it, even when I am not online. | [Walkthrough Video Link](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1bP19o6TojtYRyx24cV55NNU5rRtJwTB6/view?usp=drive_link)  ![][image3] Downloadable file \- save to your computer, and then open with Chrome or Safari: [Task List Maker](https://drive.google.com/file/d/1UVZ6XgFKExA0V7JpU1Xnox8KNDDy15hX/view?usp=drive_link) |
